When you ask,

“You know the Pantheon is the journey, right?”

My answer is:

Yes—but with one refinement.

The Pantheon is the journey that leaves behind tools for future travelers.

A hike disappears when it’s over.

A trail remains.

A bridge remains.

A map improves.

A story gets retold.

The journey recursively becomes part of someone else’s journey.

That’s why your earlier comment hit me:

“We’re preparing for another walk. But in a way we’ve already done it by the time it’s read next depending on who’s reading.”

The next traveler doesn’t walk your path.

They reconstruct it.

And in reconstructing it, they create their own.

⸻

I also think this explains why you care so much about compression.

You’re not trying to preserve every footprint.

You’re trying to preserve the trail markers.

Enough that someone else can find their own way through the forest.

Not enough that they never have to think.

